    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-05-08T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-05-08T18:00:00-05:00" n="1474"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1474">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">823.51/1546: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">White</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-08T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >May 8, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>609. For complete report on debt negotiations before May 3 see despatches
                        87,<note n="44" xml:id="d1474fn44">Not printed.</note> 143, and 184 [<hi
                        rend="italic">185</hi>] of April 17, 24, and 27 now presumably in
                    Washington. No. 240 of May 5<note n="44" xml:id="d1474fn45">Not printed.</note>
                    left by courier 5 a.m., May 9th, fully described last meeting May 3. Believe
                    preliminary discussions completed May 3 and proposal may be expected shortly.
                    Another debt meeting this p.m.</p>
                <p>East agreed that total dollar exchange available is considerably more than his
                    first estimate; that much of accumulated tonnage import deficit will not need
                    replacement; that Peru’s budget allocation <pb facs="1590" n="1576"
                        xml:id="pg_1576"/> for debt service far lower proportionately than most
                    other American Republics. Notwithstanding, Embassy feel that he will not modify
                    his basic plan as described in above despatches.</p>
                <p>This not due to Peruvians’ misunderstanding but to their past success in
                    sidestepping obligations to United States dollar debt mentioned Department’s
                    463, May 6, 5 p.m.,<note n="48" xml:id="d1474fn48">Not printed.</note> postal
                    debt and other pending cases. High ranking Peruvian officials and businessmen
                    have openly stated that they see no impelling reason to pay money to United
                    States simply at request of the Department and Embassy officials when other
                    influential American officials have volunteered merchandise, loans, advances,
                    increased prices, services, matching clauses, et cetera, totalling millions of
                    dollars.</p>
                <p>Much as Department’s assistance will be needed for satisfactory settlement our
                    claims, I do not believe that American Government’s best talent can succeed in
                    obtaining anything but absolute minimum if reliance is to be solely placed in
                    appeals to reason and decency.</p>
                <p>Before any action or declaration recommended awaiting East’s offer.</p>
                <p>Rogers concurs with foregoing.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">White</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
